04087nam a22004935i 9780226069180DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260691807 a10.7208/97802260691802doi  a(DE-B1597)524154  a(OCoLC)527639515  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB398.C63bB69 2009eb 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a1842221 aBoyarin, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocrates and the Fat Rabbis /cDaniel Boyarin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b1 halftone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: The Cheese and the Sermons: Toward a Microhistory of Ideas -- t1. In Praise of Indecorous Acts of Discourse: An Essay by Way of Introduction -- t2. “ Confound Laughter with Seriousness”: The Protagoras as Monological Dialogue -- t3. “ Confound Seriousness with Laughter”: On Monological and Dialogical Reading—the Gorgias -- t4. Jesting Words and Dreadful Lessons: The Two Voices of the Babylonian Talmud -- t5. “ Read Lucian!”: Menippean Satire and the Literary World of the Babylonian Talmud -- t6. Icarome'ir: Rabbi Me'ir’s Babylonian “Life” as Menippean Satire -- t7. “ The Truest Tragedy”: The Symposium as Monologue -- t8. A Crude Contradiction; or, The Second Accent of the Symposium -- tAppendix: On the Postmodern Allegorical -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat kind of literature is the Talmud? To answer this question, Daniel Boyarin looks to an unlikely source: the dialogues of Plato. In these ancient texts he finds similarities, both in their combination of various genres and topics and in their dialogic structure. But Boyarin goes beyond these structural similarities, arguing also for a cultural relationship. In Socrates and the Fat Rabbis, Boyarin suggests that both the Platonic and the talmudic dialogues are not dialogic at all. Using Michael Bakhtin’s notion of represented dialogue and real dialogism, Boyarin demonstrates, through multiple close readings, that the give-and-take in these texts is actually much closer to a monologue in spirit. At the same time, he shows that there is a dialogism in both texts on a deeper structural level between a voice of philosophical or religious dead seriousness and a voice from within that mocks that very high solemnity at the same time. Boyarin ultimately singles out Menippean satire as the most important genre through which to understand both the Talmud and Plato, emphasizing their seriocomic peculiarity. An innovative advancement in rabbinic studies, as well as a bold and controversial new way of reading Plato, Socrates and the Fat Rabbis makes a major contribution to scholarship on thought and culture of the ancient Mediterranean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aComic, The. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226069180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226069180.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles